Suppose that the investor's portfolio is a vector in $\mathbb{R}^n$, where $n$ is the number of different types of investments he has. Each element of the vector represents the proportion of his total investment in each type. So, the sum of all elements is 1. The investor prefers low-risk, which in this context means he wants to minimize the variance of his portfolio. 

Suppose the variance of each type of investment is given by the vector $\boldsymbol{\sigma} \in \mathbb{R}^n$, and the covariance between each pair of investments is given by the symmetric matrix $\boldsymbol{\Sigma} \in \mathbb{R}^{n \times n}$. 

The variance of the portfolio is given by $\boldsymbol{w}^T \boldsymbol{\Sigma} \boldsymbol{w}$, where $\boldsymbol{w}$ is the portfolio vector and $T$ denotes the transpose.

The investor's problem is to find the optimal portfolio that minimizes the variance subject to the constraints that the sum of all proportions is 1 and all proportions are non-negative. In mathematical terms, the problem can be stated as follows:

\begin{equation*}
\begin{aligned}
& \underset{\boldsymbol{w}}{\text{minimize}}
& & \boldsymbol{w}^T \boldsymbol{\Sigma} \boldsymbol{w} \\
& \text{subject to}
& & \boldsymbol{1}^T \boldsymbol{w} = 1, \\
&&& \boldsymbol{w} \geq \boldsymbol{0},
\end{aligned}
\end{equation*}

where $\boldsymbol{1}$ is a vector of ones in $\mathbb{R}^n$, and $\geq \boldsymbol{0}$ denotes element-wise non-negativity.

Find the general form of the optimal portfolio $\boldsymbol{w}^*$.
